    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-03-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-03-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="83"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d83">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">855.512/47</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Belgium</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 54</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-13">March 13,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your despatch No. 124 of February
                    12, 1934, with regard to the taxation of American firms in Belgium. I fully
                    concur with the position which you have taken in this matter and I hope that you
                    will continue to urge upon the Belgian Government that this taxation be
                    abandoned. Should such a system of taxation be actually put into effect it could
                    not, as you point out, do other than to drive many American firms out of the
                    Belgian market. Please continue to keep me fully informed with regard to all the
                    developments in this case.</p>
                <p>I wish to commend you upon the excellence of this report and I hope that the
                    Embassy will continue to keep me fully and currently advised of all Belgian
                    restrictions affecting American trade.</p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis B. Sayre</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
